<font color="#FF0000">MORE COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Nov 30  0:00:38 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
John Ratliff's comments are well spoken, as are those of Paul Rosenberg. There are as many points of view as there are people!<br><br>
I would like to add some additional points of view.<br><br>
Although the politics on the home front and the dramatic actions of the anti-war effort did much to bring about a greater awareness of the propaganda about the war and its conduct, there were darker and deeper forces at work that contributed to the outcome of the conflict.<br><br>
I cannot forget my feelings about how we actually fought the war on the eye to eye combat level. That's where the action was. You have to realize the mission of any soldier is to win, and to win by any means. First, winning, or defeating the enemy, is successful if the combat is supported and is done in response to a real threat. Second, the military leadership in charge of the combat must be admired and respected by the troops. Third, the troops must feel a sense of accomplishment and fulfillment of the mission.<br><br>
The Vietnam War was a failure on all three points.<br><br>
Most of us realized soon after we arrived in country that this was not a war that could be won. The Vietnamese people clearly did not enjoy our presence. The Bhuddist farmer in the average hamlet just wanted to feed his family and be left alone. To most of them, we were the invaders supporting a puppet government in Saigon which had a history of economic and religious supression of things that were not Colonial French and of the Catholic religion. That is why the major centers of NVA infiltration were in areas predominantly Bhuddist, such as the corridors through Tay Ninh and Cu Chi. Tay Ninh was a major Bhuddist religious center. I believe that US forces desicrated religious temples there, but that information is anecdotal.<br><br>
Stories of children throwing hand grenades into busses, jeeps, and trucks, were true. I recall a handgrenade tied to a mess hall tray at the 8/6th ARTY, which blew up at lunch, and blew away a lot of guys. The hand grenade did not get there by itself. I recall Mama-sans pacing off the coordinates to our command bunker in Lai Khe a few weeks before a 122mm rocket attack. I remember the little children selling dope and porn through the fence at a USO compound. I feared the legendary Dong Nai Ladies Mortar Platoon, as did most everyone else. All this stuff did not inspire confidence about our mission. Who was the enemy? I can't help but reflect with pain the children who were thrown in the breech. Doesn't that seem to be a real act of desperation?<br><br>
The Military leadership was a real contributing factor to the chaos. Although there were many fine and admired officers and NCOs, there were enough dead beats in the command ranks to make anyone puke. It seemed as if we were being used as a way to have the streakers from the Pentagon plastered with medals on the way back to their desk jobs. I was firmly convinced that the Vietnam War was just a career booster to many. The mistakes these people made were crazy.<br>
If you loose a battle plan map from a huey you would think the plans would be changed? There was an incident in the 1st Division where the plans were not changed. Guess what? It was a real hot LZ and many grunts got blown away. In general, the incompetence was so bad that the defective officers and NCOs were faced with the reality of being killed by friendly fire. The troops had a way of correcting these things.<br><br>
Finally, there was no sense of winning. No territory was ever gained. The front line was the first strand of concertina wire around your fire support base or the perimeter of your LZ or NP. You were mortared and rocketed from any direction. An assault by sappers could happen at any time. We all knew that the &quot;pacification&quot; campaign was a real joke. Some retarded general decided we should give the local people jobs inside the wire. We really had the &quot;enemy&quot; all around us. We really felt that we were not supposed to win, with all the conditions and restrictions placed on the conduct of combat.<br><br>
I lived with this 24 hours a day, seven day a week, for one year, fifteen days, eight hours, and ten minutes. I left country hollow, &quot;dead&quot;, and completely depressed. It was an esteem sucking emotional and physical meatgrinder which had no honorable purpose. Combine this with the &quot;reception&quot; back home, and it is no wonder why many of us are still screwed up.<br><br>
How can anyone win with such chaotic conditions. They called it a War? <br><br>
Two books I suggest:<br><br>
&quot;Achilles in Vietnam - Combat Trauma and the Undoing of Character&quot; by Johnathan Shay, M.D.,Ph.D., 1995, Simon and Schuster<br><br>
&quot;The Rise and Fall of an American Army&quot; by Shelby L. Stanton, 1985, Presidio Press<br><br>
Despite this, I still feel proud that what I did, I did very well. Once you become a soldier, you always remain one. My decorations, having been hidden away for twenty six years, are now up on a wall. I have deep anger and emotional scars and issues confronting me, and I live the war constantly in my mind. In time, I will acquire the skills to deal with these things.<br><br>
One final thought. It was common knowledge that the Vietnamese military was completly corrupt. No wonder the house of cards collapsed when the US really pulled out and left them to their own devices. <br>

